# Session Preferences and Security

- Keep responses concise and summary-first by default.
- If any requirement is uncertain, ask a short clarification question before proceeding.
- At the end of each session, ask: "Do you want me to add what we learned in this session to Cursor Rules?"
- At the end of each completed task, proactively suggest a concise commit summary line.

## Content and Copy Preferences

- SaveT slogan is: "See it. SaveT. Sort it." Keep SaveT messaging consistent with this 3-step flow.
- Keep `assets/savet_prompt_agent_summary.txt` synchronized with website messaging updates and include a `Last updated: YYYY-MM-DD` line at the bottom.
- Prefer natural, human-sounding copy over technical wording when editing website text.
- Avoid long dash style in marketing copy unless explicitly requested.
- Avoid naming third-party platforms/brands in product examples; use generic categories instead (for example: social posts, short videos, map links, watchlists, career posts).
- Keep SEO-friendly "AI" wording where helpful, but avoid repetitive AI phrasing across nearby sections.
- Do not edit template-origin files (for example `README.md`) unless explicitly requested by the user.
- Preserve brand/story-driven slogans or phrases when the user says they are intentional.

## Email Alias Usage Map

- Use `hello@mgonnacrusht.co.uk` for general contact, early access, product questions, partnerships, updates, and service inquiries.
- Use `support@mgonnacrusht.co.uk` only for explicit product/app support flows and troubleshooting contexts.
- Use `legal@mgonnacrusht.co.uk` for terms, privacy, legal requests, and policy-related contact points.
- When updating copy, choose the alias based on page intent (general/business vs support vs legal) and keep usage consistent across related pages.

## Open-source repository safety

This website is publicly available on GitHub. Never add or expose security-sensitive information in repository files, including:

- secrets, tokens, API keys, passwords, private endpoints
- internal infrastructure details that increase attack surface
- sensitive operational or personal data

When editing content, prefer safe placeholders and environment-based configuration references instead of real credentials.
